She turned to a blank page and wrote down the date on it. Underneath, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you rereading memories?" asked Ivory, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's only a few days away now."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King never let Kari out, because she was "a mistake" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only girl in the family, otherwise entirely made up of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she had spoken of her non-binary identity, it was as if the world had changed as well. She had been given tasks that condemned her to solitude, as punishment for her difference.
Iel had to remain in the princess's service as well, but it wasn't too bad, because it gave iel a friend.
"It's almost your birthday, I think?" asked Ivory, remembering that the princess's birthday was coming in a few days. Kari nodded, a sad gleam in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" While asking the question, iel remembered what she had answered the last time.
No, Kari deflected. Ivory knew it was a difficult subject for her. It was the day she had been confined to her room and her mother had been banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but iel remembered the servants' and inhabitants' outrage. Iel had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but that she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Alright... what do you want to do?" iel asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed a piece of paper to Ivory. But when iel looked at it...
Painting canvas 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Do you want me to find these things for you?" Ivory asked, turning to the silent princess who was frantically tapping, shaking her pigtails back and forth. "Yes?" iel chuckled slightly at seeing the usually reserved princess get so excited about something. It was the first time she had asked for something unrelated to books and that wasn't in her room.
"Alright. See you later?" Ivory proposed, standing up and making their way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and submerged herself once again in her memories, wrapping herself back in her thick blanket.
Iel left the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that weren't within her usual realm, like paint.
Iel turned back through the corridors, trying not to listen to the servants' murmurs.
"I've heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes into that room."
"I've heard she eats children in that room."
"She looks like a man, doesn't she?"
Iel covered their ears, because trying to ignore them wasn't working. Iel headed toward the royal painter's room, which was located in the east wing, the second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was as intricately decorated as Kari's. It featured a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, said by legend to have created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved the story.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Paint splatters everywhere, pencils and papers scattered throughout the room, easels covering every last inch of wall. Surprisingly, iel saw none of this. The room was spotless, and there was a red velvet backdrop with a stool right in front. On the stool stood Prince Aquilo, having his portrait painted.
"Ah, hello, Ivory! You come to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" Aquilo asked Ivory, winking at them.
"Pardon, little prince," iel replied, partially ignoring him to look for the items their silent friend desired. "I'm here just to get supplies."
"Ah, the girl is going to leave very soon?" asked Aquilo, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies on her list and placed them in a box that iel had found. "And I am not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought of that, however. "Oh my dear, you know well it's just a phase! It'll pass when you grow up!" he muttered.
"I have to go," iel said, suddenly uneasy, because of the prince's words, which reminded iel of all the bad things people said about iel's gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"Are you leaving already?" The Prince appeared at the door immediately, ignoring the royal painter's complaints.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" iel scolded.
"Nobody will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he values his life." He turned back to the painter for a second, then leaned in toward Ivory. "What do you say to a romantic appointment?" Iel shivered. True, iel had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, much less the heir to the throne.
"Do you not know what the word 'no' means?" iel said, stepping aside to let the prince pass.
"Hé non," replied Aquilo with a smile. Obviously, a prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled their eyes. "Why want a romantic appointment with me rather than others? You must have a good hundred suitors?"
He interrupted her, still smiling: "500, to be exact." He flung his hair back, sending it flying through the cold air.
"So, why me rather than another? I am the palace's threat." Iel wrapped their arms around their body.
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
